Complexes created, inferred by SHARED REACTIONS
This first mechanism for inference of protein complexes focuses on multiple polypeptides that
catalyze a common reaction.  A complex is inferred for each set of subunits that catalyze the
same reaction(s), contain subunit-related words in their names, and whose genes are near one
another in the genome. After the complex inference, the reactions are marked as catalyzed
by the complexes instead of by the polypeptides.
Cytochrome bc1 complex cytochrome b subunit
Cytochrome bc1 complex cytochrome c subunit
Complexes created by SHARED REACTIONS and augmented by NAME STRING ANALYSIS
After complexes were created by shared reactions, sometimes the inference
by name analysis may also find matches with one of the previously created complexes,
given that all polypeptide name strings are analyzed, even of those polypeptides that are
already in a complex.  In such a match, additional polypeptides will be added to the complex
that was based merely on shared reactions, instead of creating a separate but partial complex.

Complexes created, inferred by NAME STRING ANALYSIS
This third mechanism for inference of protein complexes analyzes shared subunit-related
words in the names of several polypeptides. First, polypeptides are grouped together by
shared 'core strings.' A core string aims to capture the core function of a polypeptide
and is derived from a polypeptide name by removing subunit-related words and other
extraneous markup (for example, the core string for 'tryptophan synthase, subunit alpha'
is simply 'tryptophan synthase'). Next, a complex is created for each such a polypeptide
grouping unless all polypeptides have identical names.

Complexes created, inferred by ABC TRANSPORTER ANALYSIS
This specialized protein complex inference mechanism analyzes the subunits
in one operon, of which some subunits contain the substring 'ABC transport'.
Other subunits in the operon are added to the complex, if they contain words like
